### Week 2

**Feature 4 — Tenant Manifest fetch + `useTenantStore`**
```
After successful login, fetch the Tenant Manifest (branding, featureFlags, navigation,
workflowConfig, permissions, locale — see the architecture doc's TenantManifest
interface) via React Query with a long staleTime, and store it in a Zustand
useTenantStore for synchronous access outside of React Query hooks (e.g., inside
apiCaller interceptors or utility functions). Invalidate this query when a
'manifest:updated' socket event fires (stub the socket call for now, wire it for
real in Week 4). Every other feature from here forward reads tenant config from this
store — never introduce a second source of truth for tenant/role/flag data.
```

**Feature 5 — CASL ability integration + `<PermissionGate>`**
```
Wire up @casl/ability and @casl/react. Build an AbilityProvider that constructs the
CASL ability instance from manifest.permissions (the resolved rules for the current
user) and exposes it via useAbility(). Build the <PermissionGate action subject data
children> component with this exact three-way behavior:
1. Allowed -> render children normally.
2. Not allowed, role-based (the subject/action exists conceptually for this tenant
   but this user's role lacks it) -> render children in a disabled state, wrapped
   with a tooltip: "You don't have [edit] rights for this. Contact your
   [nearest role above them in the tenant's role hierarchy] to request access." The
   bracketed role must be resolved dynamically from manifest role hierarchy data,
   not hardcoded.
3. Not allowed, feature-flag-based (the capability is entirely unavailable for this
   tenant) -> render nothing. No tooltip, no disabled state — there's no one to ask.
4. Not allowed, scope-based (e.g. another branch's record) -> render nothing, same
   as flag-based — don't disclose that the record/action exists.
Write unit tests with fixtures for at least 3 roles proving each of these 4 branches
renders correctly.
```

**Feature 6 — App shell layout**
```
Build the persistent app shell: collapsible left sidebar (240px expanded / 64px
collapsed) rendering manifest.navigation filtered through ability.can('view', ...) —
a nav item must not render at all if the role has zero access, not just be
disabled. Top bar (56px) with: global search trigger, notification bell (static for
now), tenant switcher (only rendered if the user belongs to multiple tenants —
otherwise omit entirely, don't show a single-item dropdown), avatar/account menu.
Route-level code splitting: lazy-load route bundles grouped by permission area (e.g.
admin routes in their own chunk) so a collector's bundle never even downloads admin
screen code. Responsive breakpoint: sidebar auto-collapses under 1024px viewport width.
```

