### Week 13

**Feature 31 — OAuth2/OIDC SSO**
```
Add "Sign in with company email" SSO alongside the existing email/password flow
(Feature 2), supporting Google Workspace and Microsoft Entra ID as OIDC providers.
Implementation:
- Use Authorization Code flow with PKCE (never Implicit flow) — this is a
  browser-based SPA, so PKCE is mandatory for security.
- The login page shows both the email/password form AND SSO buttons; which SSO
  providers appear (if any) is tenant-configurable — read from
  manifest.ssoProviders (or equivalent), don't hardcode both buttons as always-on.
- On the SSO callback route, exchange the authorization code via the backend (the
  frontend never handles client secrets) and receive the same access-token-in-memory
  + httpOnly-refresh-cookie pattern as the password flow — SSO must not introduce a
  second, less-secure token storage path.
- Handle the "user's SSO email doesn't match any existing account" case with a
  clear message, not a silent failure or generic error.
- If the tenant's manifest indicates SSO is mandatory (password login disabled for
  this org), hide the password form entirely rather than showing it disabled.
Acceptance: verify token storage is identical between the two auth methods, verify
PKCE is actually being used (inspect the auth request), and verify a login attempt
against a tenant with SSO-only configured never renders a password field.
```

**Feature 32 — MFA (TOTP)**
```
Build TOTP-based 2FA: setup flow (QR code + manual entry key, backup codes shown
once and downloadable), and the login-time challenge step. Support tenant-level
policy: manifest may indicate MFA is mandatory for all users at this org, in which
case a user without MFA configured is forced into setup immediately after their
first successful login before reaching the app shell — don't let them skip it.
```

